[3] France (Reunion Island)
Date: Thu, 2 Mar 2006 06:57:35 -0500 (EST)
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Liberation.fr, 1 Mar 2006 [trans by A-Lan Banks; edited]
<http://www.liberation.fr/page.php?Article=363606>

Chikungunya and dengue viruses were detected for the first time simultaneously
in 15 patients on Reunion. If the co-infection is confirmed, it will have to
be determined whether the patients were infected by mosquitoes transporting
both viruses or if the infections were separate, as was announced today in an
official statement by the Regional Administration of Sanitary and Social
Affairs (DRASS).
Chikungunya and dengue are transmitted by the same mosquito, the famous _Aedes
albopictus_.
The cases remain to be confirmed by the national Center [for Arboviruses] of
Lyon. The situation is far from being clear. According to Doctor Henriette de
Valk, member of the Interregional Epidemiology Cell of Reunion-Mayotte
(CIRE) "Chikungunya infection can influence the results of dengue tests."
[She can't have said that, it's absolutely untrue. CHIKV is an alphavirus,
the 4 dengue viruses are flaviviruses. There is zero crossing between them in
lab tests. - Mod.JW, former head of CDC's dengue lab in the Caribbean].
According to CIRE, "the occurrence of isolated cases of dengue is comparable
with the background noise observed in 2005" on Reunion, where on average 2
cases of dengue were recorded per month. The last epidemic of dengue on the
island in 2004 infected several hundred people.
The epidemic of "Chik" has affected 157 000 people since March 2005.
At the highest levels of French government, the new risks of the epidemic are
regarded as extremely alarming. At a Council of Ministers this morning Jacques
Chirac called for adaptating the alarm and monitoring system "vis-a-vis
emergent infectious diseases."
